title: Ear clip for Sony VH110 Bluetooth Headset

description.text:
I had this Sony Ericsson VH110 bluetooth headset for ages, but a year ago the clip that held it in place over the ear broke off. But with a 3D-printer at hand it's a simple matter of some image editing and 3d CAD to create a replacement.
The EarClip Small - file is the same size as the original headset clip, way to tight for me.
The EarClip Larger - file is scaled up 10% and fits me perfectly.

Printer:

Velleman Vertex K8400

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0,2mm/slice

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I used PLA, but I expect that ABS would work equally well.

Steps to create this was:
  1. Photograph the original clip against a white paper, with alot of light, with the phone.
  2. Open up the picture in GIMP and retouch the image, adjust contrast and brightness.
  3. Load the image into Inkscape and trace the contours into a SVG vector image.
  4. Enter TinkerCAD, import SVG image and extrude it to the thickness needed.
  5. Scale the image to be 100%of the original.
  6. Test print, took 4 min (excluding heat-up) on my Vertex K8400
  7. Modify CAD model, enlarging the clip (but not the connecting clip) 10%
  8. Print final version, 4 minutes later and I have a comfortable fully working BT headset.

description.text:
Perfect application for owning a 3d printer:
Saw other cyclists having this hot mudguard on the back of their saddle. Looked it up and it costs about 10$. Since it is just a piece of plastic I asked myself - why not print my own version of it?

There you go! After some iterations I managed to find a design which fits just perfectly into the frame of the bottom side of the saddle. This design totally saves my ass on a rainy day! Since the dimensions of the bike saddles frame are standardized, this mudguard should fit to your bike as well.

Mounting:

Make sure to carefully slide the mudguard into the frame of your saddle. Check out the last picture in the gallery, which shows the bottom side. You will realize that you first need to clip both rods into the provided gaps and then slide the nose of the mudguard into the thin slit of saddle mount. Moving the whole mudguard a little to the front will slightly tilt it upwards, which makes your bike look really hot!

Have Fun saving your ass and share your makes, I would love to see other colors on other bikes!

UPDATE

There are two versions now:
bike_mudguard.stl -> is the original design with a total length of 279mm, which fits perfectly on the printerbed of the prusa i3 mk2 if you position it diagonal
mudguard_short -> is the new and shorter version for all smaller printbeds. With a total length of 250mm it is designed to fit to the print bed of the anet a8.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

Notes:

The total length of the mudguard is 279mm and easily fits on the printbed of my prusa i3 mk2 if I rotate it by 45% to be diagonal.

The height of the flat part is 0.6mm which totally sufficient for this purpose. I printed the mudguard with a layerheight of 0.15mm so I ended up having 4 layers for the thing part.

Adjusting the infill will not make any difference since there is no big volume at all. Having 4 shell layers lead to a 100% solid part.

I was using PLA which performs very well. It is capable of holding off the water... for a couple of times now already. ABS or PETG might be more durable. Would be nice if somebody could give it a try!

description.text:
I bought a FlashForge Creator Pro 2017 for my business and was frustrated by the hard to reach and clumsy rear spool holders. After not finding a good alternative, I decided to design my own. These spool holders attach to the printer using some of the existing screws (4 on top, 1 on the side for each). They each require a 63 inch (1.6 meter) length of 6mm outer diameter, 4mm inner diameter PTFE tubing to rout the filament to the hot end. My source: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01A42FZY4/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1.

I only have one spool holder installed currently, as I have optimized my machine for fast ABS printing. I've been been printing with this spool holder for many hours now, and it's been working perfectly. I hope this helps all the other makers out there looking to use their FFCP 2017 to pump out lots of parts! If you have any suggestions for improvements, please let me know.

I made some ‘sympathy lamps.’ Or ‘relationship lamps.’ Or ‘friendship lamps.’ Call them whatever you want. Here’s the deal: You push the button on one lamp, and they both light up. You push the button on either lamp while they’re lit? They both turn off. They’ll turn off automatically after about 10 minutes. They’re connected via wifi. They will work over the internet. They’re a fun way to let someone know you’re thinking about them.

I made mine using the heart found here.
Customize them however you want. A batman logo seems like an easy win.

This requires some non-3d printed parts. Everything can be picked up from adafruit. Their “photon starter set” has a lot of what you’ll need.
2x 5mm LED (I went with blue)
2x Particle Photon with headers
2x Small breadboard
4x Female to male leads
4x Male to male leads
2x 220 ohm resistors
2x 30mm Arcade button (I went with clear)
Some super glue

Post-printing setup:
Attach the particle photon to your breadboard.
Attach the female to male leads to your LEDs.
The positive LED lead goes to D0 on the photon.
The negative LED lead goes to ground on the photon.
Run the resistor between ground and D4 on the photon.
Attach male to male leads to the arcade button.
Run the arcade button leads through the hole.
Connect one lead to the 3v3 on the photon.
Connect the other to D4.
Snap the button into place.
Determine where the LED touches the cone on the lid. Apply super glue to that area of the LED and hold it to the cone until the glue cures.

Follow photon’s instructions for registering and flashing the device. Use the code provided in the .txt file. You will need to add a customized random string for both the 'myId' and 'buddyId' variables. (To be more specific: You will generate two random strings, random.org is a good resource for that. On one device, use stringA as 'myId' and stringB as 'buddyId.' On the other device put stringA as the 'buddyId' and stringB as 'myId.')

Make sure they work as expected.

Close the lid.

description.text:
Update 5/11/17: IF YOU USED THE PREVIOUS VERSION, REPRINT THE NEW ONE

I widened the lower piezo mount to fit snugly around the hotend, and extend the full height rather than an outer lip only, and also widened the center spacer that goes on top of the hotend. These changes add a lot of stability, and don't affect the sensitivity at all.

This is a simple, quick printing mount for the 713maker Hotend mount (http://713maker.com/mounts.html ) for use with a 27mm piezo disc z-probe. I used moriquendi's piezo board (you can find a link on reprapforums) for the piezo.

The design is pretty straight forward. The "bottom" piece goes around the top of your hotend. The Center goes on top of your hotend, around your bowden tube. (Be sure to clip your bowden in... you'll lose access to the clip once this is on). Alternatively, I used a nylon spacer from my local hardware store in place of the printed one. Just be sure the height of the center spacer and the outer ring match up! You may need to adjust the height of them depending on how your hotend fits in the groovemount. You want them equal, or the center part just slightly higher.

Then goes the piezo (with a 5mm hole in the center to fit around your bowden) with the ceramic bit (and wires) facing up. Orient the top part so the wires line up with the gap, and then attach your retaining plate for the hotend mount. I recommend the "Bowden" one from 713maker, as it helps keep your bowden from resting against the piezo.

I do recommend sanding the top surface of all your printed parts with a very fine sandpaper before installing them, just so they're as flat as possible.

That's it!

More info on piezo z-probes at these links:
http://reprap.org/wiki/Piezo-electric_sensors
http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?1,635075

I printed this to keep the seed for a trezor hardware wallet.
The idea is to make shure the seed has not been compromised (read) by any person.
Therefore the paper gets inserted during the printprocess of the closed closed object.
Once the print has finished the paper can only be removed by breaking the capsule.
Of cause any paper can be inserted as long as it fits physically.

Printed using spiral vase. But it should print normal as well, but it will probably need more force to break it, depending on your outer shells.
Once the print has reached a reasonable height, pause the print lift the noozle up by 100mm or so. Insert the paper, manual extrude some filament and move the noozle exactly the same amount down you moved it up before. Then resume the print.
Once finished the paper should be enclosed completely.

description.text: This is a model of the Pod companions from the game Nier:Automata. The elbows and fingers are connected by articulated ball-and-socket joints, and the elbow-to-body connection can also rotate as well.

Printer:

Notes:

I printed the body and arms with a raft to be safe, while everything else minus the head and stand was printed with a brim. The orientation they appear here on thingiverse is the orientation in which I printed them. I noticed that the sockets worked better when they were printed in a way so that they were standing straight up, so maybe that's something to take into consideration.

Here's what I printed each part at:
Head: 30% infill
Body: 100% infill (this was probably overkill, but I was having issues with sections breaking)
Arms: 40% infill
Everything else: 20% infill

All Pod parts were at 0.2 mm layer height, Display stand was 0.3 mm but these can be changed

Elbows

I originally had issues with the elbow-to-body joint being very loose and falling out. I edited them and as they are now, they will probably be printed a little too big to fit right away. I manually file them down after printing until they are just small enough to squeeze in there and fit snugly if done correctly.

Connecting the head to the body

The body does not have any joint to connect to the head, it must be glued onto the platform. Personally I used Testors "cement for plastic models" to attach it and it works great.

Here is my first drone frame design posted on thingiverse :)
It's a long time i wanted to design a 1S mini racer in brushless and not coreless.

It is a beta (fully functional) but next improvement is a pod.

XENO100 is a 100 mm between motors
It support Motors 0703 and 1103, 1104, 1105 and propellers up to 65 mm

Stay tuned!

or BR0703 15.000kv : http://bit.do/Motors-BR0703-15000kv

description.text:
Just a small modification of CBikers Thing 634890.

First of all a big thank to CBiker and his, let's say "CTC Bizer Compendium"!
Really a must follow for all those who just started with one of these Chinese Makerbot/Flash Forge clones.
Only, it was driving me mad trying to print this backwall filament guide with my out of the box configurated printer, not having updated any axis guide or firmware to Sailfish.
But having it brand new I was angry about losing warrenty.
So I was thinking to myself, why printing something with rafts and supports, that also does require bought-by fasteners and straps.

description.text:
This is an adapter to mount the Mosaic Palette Scroll Wheel to a Makergear M2 printer.

It comes in 2 pieces: a base and the cup to hold the scroll wheel. The base is to be permanently bolted to the printer using existing holes and the cup will easily slide in/out of it (for single filament use). The base could be easily modified to allow its use on other printers. No modification of the cup should be needed.

The cup itself has a helical cutout for the Scroll Wheel’s cable. The geometry should prevent the scroll wheel from jiggling out of the cup under use without any tape/adhesive necessary to hold it in place.

There are two variations of the cup. A simple one-piece/one-color version and a multipart/multicolor version with helical bands mimicking the cutout for the cord. It’s a purely gratuitous use of color, but what the heck, with a Palette, I can do that now!

This is a little drone mounted, radio controlled disc launcher I made.

The discs got about 20' with the spring tension I set. I didn't wan't to go much stronger than that for fear of hurting someone.

I put a logo on the discs I made for an event I attended. I left a few example discs in the model, as well as a blank that you can cut however you want.

The sketchup model is included to make it easier to modify for those who use sketchup.

All together, its a pretty simple build, just lots of parts. A couple of them needed support, you'll be able to tell which. I printed the spring quadrant and cam with 100% fill to make sure they were tough enough to handle the spring, everything else was 25%.

Fully assembled with electronics and fully loaded with discs, the whole assembly weighed in at nearly a half a pound. The Mavic Pro we mounted it on had no trouble at all with it.

You'll see in the video that it looked like it was firing multiple discs. It was popping discs out of the top of the hopper as it shot, so I added a swiveling lid to the hopper but don't have a video of that in action yet.

Let me know if you have any questions!!

It uses a few non printed parts you'll have to scrounge.

Gearmotor: The unit I used is all over Amazon and eBay, search 'Gearmotor Tire'. Its yellow and usually comes with a wheel. Usually about $5 each.

Radio: I used a 12v key fob radio with a relay receiver from Amazon. Seemed like there were plenty of options for around $15.

Battery: I used a 450 mah, 3S, 11.1v LiPo cell from Amazon, was about $10.

Spring: I straightened and re-bent a 2" 'safety pin' from Lowes. If you can't find that, any bit of spring steel with that is almost more than you can bend by hand should do. The stronger you find, the better distance you'll get, until the motor can't pull it anymore.

description.text:
Nintendo officially announced that they are discontinuing the NES Classic. So instead of paying the outrageous prices people are wanting for them on eBay, lets build our own! I designed a case for a Raspberry Pi 3 to make it look and function like a SNES. With it running RetroPie, we can not only play our favorite SNES and NES games, we can play almost any retro video game we want. Lets build a SNES Mini.
Here is the video I made on how I designed and built the system from start to finish: https://youtu.be/mymHcEU9BsQ
UPDATE: 5/4/17
Several people, myself included, have had issues with the power button "bed" in the bottom of the case. It's stringy underneath and the two small support legs break off during printing. I created a small part (SNES Mini Case Bottom 1.0 Fix) that can be printed to insert where the legs are supposed to be (thanks s40rtaaa for the idea) if you have already printed the bottom of the case. I have also renamed the original bottom to SNES Mini Case Bottom 1.0. I've updated the model so that there is more support and made the power button bed it's own separate piece so it can be printed and glued in later. The new parts are SNES Mini Case Bottom 1.1 and SNES Mini Power Button Bed. Hope this helps.
UPDATE: 5/7/17
The USB extension cables I originally used from Monoprice were out so I had to use the USB 3.0 extension cables from Monoprice instead. The ends are a tad bit smaller so I redesigned the controller ports and uploaded them. They are SNES Mini Controller ___ Small.
UPDATE: 6/1/17
Monoprice is currently out of the 1.5' USB extension cables, both the USB 2.0 and 3.0 versions. I am happy to report that the 3' USB 2.0 USB extension cables can be wound in the case and will work for the project.
UPDATE: 7/12/17
I've created another Raspberry Pi 3 case, this time it's a Sega Genesis. I'm selling the files for it on my Etsy shop: https://www.etsy.com/shop/epicallygeeky Here is the video I made for it as well: https://youtu.be/YBzDKsn49Aw

description.text:
Once I decided that I was going to drive my new Wanhao D7 using a Raspberry Pi running NanoDLP it was time to start thinking about how to keep things neat and tidy. This is version one of that effort. It is probably going to stay version 1 for a while as I finally have resin arriving tomorrow!

This thing is now really two things. Since my workspace is far from level I decided that I needed adjustable feet. When I did that it was noticeable that there was room under the printer for the Raspberry Pi. Hence this new thing. I have kept the RPi mounted "bare" on the base as an aid to cooling it. Note that the photo shows the RPi in the center when the STL shows it to the side. The side is better for running of the video cable.

The original thing was built around the Raspberry Pi case by 0110-MP that you can find here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:922740.

One last update! This thing is now three things. In this latest variant I moved the RPi to the front and added some space to tie down cables. There is also a special joiner that fits on one side where the other would have been blocked. You will see what I mean.

Hardware required: M6 Bolts and Nuts. Lengths of 20-25 or even 30mm will work. Ideally a half nut to use as the brake. Also ideally a hex head bolt though you can use a nut as shown on a round head bolt.

author: dmmaggio

title: FT5 aero setup for Volcano with partcooler

description.text:
A redesign for the Aero on the FT5.
All parts are designed to limit as much as possible the need for printing support.
I tried also to get the maximum flat area on the bed.
The partcooler with the 40mm fan can be reused from that design.

Changes
New front with a larger support area to attach a BLTouch, IR or inductive and other sensors (will post a new mount for the BLTouch optimized for the 8.3mm Z-distance to the nozzle for both Volcano and V6)
3 new backs
1- just a back without anything extra
2-Back with new support for partcooler with 40mm fan as in the first design
3-Back with support for a standard blower

Blower
Blower sits in a seat integrated in the backpart (Aero_back_with_blower_support_v2.stl).
The blower is attached with the blower outlet part (Aero_Blower_outlet_v1.stl) : 2 bolts (M3 30mm) are needed. The nuts slide in the pockets in the backpart. The outlet part sits also in a pocket in the backpart.
Stepper has to be mounted before the blower is assembled!
There are 2 shrouds available : one for the Volcano, one for the V6. They are connected with bolts and nuts to the blower outlet part.

Partcooler with 40mm fan
The partcooler is mounted with 2 bolts&nuts on the 'back with partcooler support'.
See previous design for pictures and STL.

Attention
I don't use a V6 anymore. I will not test this configuration. See for a compatible cooler here

Printing
Support will be needed for the back :
-blower support for the pockets holding the M3 nylocks
-Beltlocks
The Blower Outlet part will need more support. This should be quite easy to remove from the internal channel as it is quite large, short and accessible.
Print the partcooler shrouds vertically then I do not expect you will need support.Only the shroud with the 40mm fan needs a bit of support.

All parts in the pictures are printed in ABS with a 0,6mm nozzle, 0,32mm layer, 5 perimeters (I want a bit of extra around the bolts if I need to clear the holes), 3 top- and bottom layers, 50% infill
Pay attention for the belt lcks. Since the dents are quite small, this has to be printed with a 0,4mm nozzle (or smaller). Print the locks on their side with the dents in profile.

Testing remarks
20170501
Back(s), front, and BLTouch mount are ok.
I will modify the blower mount a little bit on two places :

  • the pin fixing the upper part has to be a little bit higher
  • I will make the connection to the shroud flat instead of with a small profile.
    Shroud (at least for the Volcano) has to be a bit lower and more near and aside of the nozzle. It now blows too much on the Volcano itself.

I must say that I am a bit disappointed on the airflow the blower generates. This was better with the 40x40x25mm axial fan.On the other hand, the design is a little bit shorter and more compact on the back.

20170504
Added a new blower mount. Changes : larger outlet, thicker connection for fixing the shroud and an adjustment on the pin holding the upper part of the blower
Made a new shroud. Going back to my old model with two outlets on both sides of the block. Total surface of the air channels is at least the outlet surface of the blower with a larger chamber just before the split in 2 shrouds. The shroud should be printed outlets up and does not need support anymore.

20170505
Removed Work-In-Progress tag. Happy with the result. Go ahead.
The latest version of the shroud is doing its job well. The focus of the air beams is around 8mm under the nozzle and the flow is much better then with the first version.The overall section is better.

20180227
I got the remark that the belt cannot move freely. I recommend using my X-pulley and X-stepper mount&X-endstop as these go together. Sorry for any inconvenience by not mentioning this. See the extra pictures added. I do not use a cable chain neither.

description.text:
This was an experiment, so beware... I wanted to experiment with "spiral vase" mode with my 1.2mm volcano nozzle, and also wanted to learn how to parametrically generate shapes in OpenSCAD. This was the result. The shape is entirely generated mathematically in openscad, once facet at a time! If you want to play with this, download and READ the *.scad file - it's well commented and has a lot of config options, but is only about a page long.

Warning: this design does not produce a closed STL file, just the perimeter. I rely on Slic3r to close the object for me, then print with two solid bottom layers and the rest in spiral vase mode. It happens to turn out the way I want - but only "happens to". YMMV.

The shape itself is the product of two sinusoidal waves, with the period and amplitude configurable.

description.text:
This is a simple print to screw the threaded rods on the Anet A8 down to a surface. Dimensions are suitable for use with 4mm screw dia self tapping screws into wood. A flange or dome topped screw is preferable to spread the compression.

The design is based on the center of the threaded rod being 23mm from the surface on which it is mounted. If someone specifically requests it I'll post a version which would allow you to customise the distance and the size of the mount to suit different diameter screws and threaded rod.

include <bezier_curve.scad>;

I wanted a fidget spinner cap that I could swap out and/or not have to glue. This was a perfect fit and works great. I made the stop points on the bearing large enough to hopefully fit any fidget spinner that uses a 608 Ball Bearing.

Feel free to rework or use as needed.

UPDATE:
Created a V2 model that has a the gap between the bearing and the cap a bit smaller; just in case its too big for some people. Also including the Fusion 360 file for anyone who wants to edit the model for themselves.

UPDATE V2 (May, 5th 2017)
Post Production: After having a few discussions with a couple of people trying to print these STL files, I realized I forgot to mention that you may have to adjust your printers retraction settings to ensure that there are no little pieces of unwanted plastic on the threads (which will prevent the parts to mate properly). Or, what can be done is a little sanding on the male threads with scotch brite to make sure they mate.

I've printed a few extras to make sure the files were good and I did get a couple pairs that had to be worked on before they threaded together correctly. The threads are very small, so make sure to print them at .100mm or better to ensure a good thread. If you increase the size of the file, the pitch diameter will be incorrect and not thread properly (so avoid increasing the model).

They may not look it, but the model, due to the threads, are a bit complicated and you will want to make sure your printers settings are on point. Feel free to comment if you guys have any further issues and I will be sure to try and help as best as I can.

UPDATE V3:
Alright! I have a new update for everyone. Even after a few minor tweaks to the last update, things still caused people some major issues with the threads. So, this time, I completely redesigned the caps in order to have thicker threads; making it much easier to print on FDM style printers. You will still want to keep the resolution/layer height to .100mm (100 microns) max in order to have a nice, clean thread. I have also included the .step file, so if anyone has any further issues and wishes to try to fix or remix the STL files; feel free to do so.

I so glad to see so many people have downloaded my model and hope you guys keep on enjoying my design. Happy Printing and keep those Fidgets a Spinning!

title: X Axis Motor Mount and Idler

description.text:
This design will not receive any further revisions (unless someone specifically asks and I find the time).

If for some reason you want the source OpenSCAD file for this particular design to make a customised version please send me a message.

I will continue to update my current design https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2639980 if I find any areas for further improvements.

This is a different version of printable x-Axis parts for the left and right sides of the x carriage. The design prefers features that can generally be easily printed over optimal filament use. It incorporates holes for a total of 8 M3 square nuts (4 for each leadscrew part). The x idler position is slightly wider to accomodate toothed idler bearings so this file is not recommended if you do not have an idler wheel with raised edges to keep the belt in line.

I would also not recommend mixing these parts with those from other designs as the dimensions and rod positions may vary slightly from designer to designer. That said if you have the knowledge to be able to identify any possible problems please feel free to give it a go!

Note that my photo for the x motor mount shows an additional part which is not of my own design. If you're looking for the part attached to the front of the x motor I obtained this to print from the following user's thing: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776429

The x motor part also uses an endstop mounting position similar to the version of the Anet A8 machine which was available at time of writing.

Updates

11/11/2017 - Distance between horizontal x axis smooth rod centers is 45mm.

05/11/2017 - Note that the distance between the centers of the bearing hole and leadscrew hole in this design is 22mm.

31/08/2017 - Upload of first iteration of tensioner to pair with the x idler. It has supports built into the design for printing with a 0.4mm nozzle. The supports are under the two prongs and in the gap where the idler is mounted. Note that for an optimal fit for your idler you may wish to leave half a millimetre of the cylinder in the centre so that the idler might not rub against the sides of the part.

Note any darker / smoother looking parts of the model are where I ended up making a repair to my print. The settings I used were not quite right for the end print.

Notes:

Using a brim of 6 perimeters and 1 layer thickness and 3 top and bottom layers. I have also specifically added supports for the x motor's large hole and square part of the rectangular part of the slot. Depending on your printing experience and material choice you may find this unnecessary.

For ease of assembly you may wish to drill out the small holes with a 3mm drill bit. Bearings can be manually pushed the first few millimeters and then moved flush to the surface using a clamp over both ends (gradually tightening). You can also push on the top of the bearing to break the friction.

8mm holes can also be lightly cleaned out with an 8mm drill bit if there is too much friction to install the rods easily. I have aimed to ensure that there is excess space on the motor side to push rods in allowing a little more flexibility with the stock A8 x axis smooth rods.
Designed in OpenSCAD using visual observations of the stock parts and trial and error prints with test fitting to refine the design.

description.text:
The Tronxy P802M X-Axis end-carriage is not a 'through' design, and traditional Anet A8 belt-tensioners, which rely on looping the belt past the end of the right end-carriage, will not work on it.

This compact design simply snaps on to the X-axis rail by the right carriage which:

  • adds more tension to your x-axis belt (e.g. when it stretches due to aging), and
  • has the added benefit of making the x-axis belt loop more run more 'parallel' to each other (the Tronxy uses a much larger bearing than the diameter of the stepper pinion gear).

Assembly:

  1. Print all three parts and perform any clean-up or sanding required. Use a Q-Tip to clean the outside and inside cylindrical faces of the bearing with alcohol to remove any grease/oil.
  2. Test fit the pulley wheel cap (WheelB) to the pulley wheel (WheelA). Make sure the cap's groove is clear of debris and that the cap fits snug and the two circular guard flanges are parallel to each other.
  3. Lightly coat the inside barrel of the pulley wheel with CA glue (be sure to wipe off any excess) and press a 5x11x4mm bearing into the wheel. Once flush in the wheel, use a dowel (a X-acto knife holder also works) that is >4mm to push the bearing all the way until it's completely seated within the pulley.
  4. Lightly coat the i. rim of the pulley wheel (where it contacts the wheel cap), as well the ii. groove of the wheel cap with CA, and press the cap tightly onto the pulley. Let it set overnight.
  5. Use a small butane torch (or cigarette-lighter) to heat up just the nub of the tensioner. Be very gentle (very quickly brush the flame across the nub 2-3x). Press the assembled pulley-wheel onto the nub. Make sure it's seated fully and while the nub is softened, adjust the plane of the pulley so that that it's straight and square and will not wobble as the pulley is rotated on the post.
  6. Once the nub has cooled down, remove the pulley. Coat the cylindrical face of the nub with CA glue (be absolutely sure to wipe off any excess) and re-insert the pulley. Let it set overnight.

title: Anet A8 Bowden E3D V6 Conversion Guide

description.text:
This guide will cover how to convert your Anet A8 from it's stock extruder, to an all metal Bowden E3D V6 (or clone) setup.

After seeing a large amount of Anet A8 users wanting to upgrade to an E3D V6 Bowden extruder, and a lack of information regarding the upgrade, I have decided to post a complete guide detailing how I went about the upgrade. When I did this myself, the lack of information caused me to repeatedly wait for parts, leaving my printer torn apart for nearly 3 weeks. Hopefully after reading this, you will be able to avoid doing the same.
Note: I have enough spare hardware lying around, that I was able to complete this project without buying hardware. As a result I do not know what is needed or where. If someone can figure this out and provide feedback including this information I'd be happy to include it! (The .stl is irrelevant. Just included for publishing :D)

Step 1) Before you take your printer apart, you need to print a few parts:

  • E3D V6 Bowden carriage (I chose this one: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2099577)
  • Extruder motor mount (I chose this one: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2146021)
  • (Optional) X Axis Cable Chain (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2105040 (fully compatible with the carriage I chose))

Step 2) There are several parts you need to buy, here's what I bought: (all links at bottom)

  • 30mm 12V fan
  • Fan Duct (could also print it, but I just bought it)
  • M6 bowden connector, this one gives you a spare, and a spare bowden tube
  • (Recommended) Spare thermistors, incase of breakage during assembly

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01L2LFCWG/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01FBPQF1Q/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B014G85MO0/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01F1XTRGI/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01B41K7OM/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Step 3) Disassembly (explaining this from memory, may not be perfect)

  1. Heat extruder, remove filament, let cool
  2. Remove squirrel cage fan
  3. Undo hex bolts holding fan and heat sink (while not ideal, I reused these), remove fan and heat sink
  4. Remove screw on underside of extruder, holding the motor to the carriage
  5. Loosen the M6 bolt on the underside (you will need this later)
  6. Disconnect the extruder motor
  7. Slide the extruder assembly off the carriage, and out of the way
  8. Unscrew carriage from the mounts on the guide rods, set carriage aside (you will reuse the screws
  9. Remove heat cartridge and thermistor from heat block (you will be reusing these)
  10. Remove nozzle throat from heat block (ideally you will be reusing this)
  11. Move heat block and nozzle off to the side. You do not need these
  12. Remove Z axis guide rod cover from the side in which the extruder motor will reside (save the screw)

Step 4) Assembly (The exciting part?) Be sure to cable manage when necessary!

  1. Install new carriage using original screws.
  2. Remove screws from E3D heat block for cartridge and thermistor
  3. Insert cartridge into heat block, tighten corresponding screw firmly
  4. Insert thermistor, carefully tighten screw, do not over tighten
  5. Slide E3D into carriage
  6. Install cap over Extruder using screws
  7. Screw 30mm fan into fan duct.
  8. Slide fan and duct onto the E3D's heat sink.
  9. Install squirrel cage fan, and any desired cooling nozzle
  10. Runs screws through the carriage on either side of the extruder, to attach the X Axis belt to
  11. Install the extruder motor mount on the top of the printer
  12. Align all the parts of the motor as they would originally exist, and using the original screws in conjunction with nuts (along with one more appropriate screw) attach the motor to the mount. The input side of the motor should face toward the outside of the printer
  13. Connect the Bowden connector to the stock nozzle throat using the M6 bolt from the original extruder. (This bolt and throat trick is not necessary, but makes loading filament much easier. I have not had issues with this connection, as sketchy as it may seem)
  14. Screw the nozzle throat into the output of the extruder motor, until it is an appropriate distance from the gear and bearing.
  15. Connect the bowden tube between the motor and extruder.

Step 5) Initial testing (technically skippable):

  • Be weary of the fact that the extruder is lower than before, make the necessary adjustments to prevent the nozzle from crashing
  • Hold in screw on extruder motor, feed the filament until it is coming out the heated extruder
  • Try a print! (You may need to reduce/temporarily disable retraction)

Step 6) Firmware
As noted in the thing summary for the carriage, the X positioning of the extruder is slightly different. As you probably noticed in Step 5, this leads to prints being offset from the center of the bed. You can either account for this in your starting GCODE in your slicer of choice, or you can reflash firmware. Because of it's availability, I updated to Skynet. I do not recommend fighting with Skynet unless you also have an auto-leveling sensor. I dislike my current firmware configuration strongly (if anyone can tell me where I can find the stock firmware, that would be appreciated). Long story short, you need the Arduino IDE, and once you open the files for your desired firmware, find the file called "configuration.h", and open it. use CTRL + F and find the string "X_MIN_POS", and set this value to -10. Compile the firmware, and push it to the printer over USB.
Step 7) Enjoy!
Print a retraction test or two and dial your settings in, once you re-familiarize yourself with your printer, have fun increasing your print speeds!

I wish I had found a better solution as far as firmware is concerned, but I have made this as detailed as possible. Please provide feedback regarding the completeness of this, and let me know if there's anything I missed!

(Please note: I am not responsible for any damages or injuries caused while following this guide. Thanks)

Alchemist Prosthetic Hand. Still a work in progress.

Why is this hand named after Dàzǔ Huìkě?
Legend has it that Bodhidharma initially refused to teach Huike. Huike stood in the snow outside Bodhidharma’s cave all night, until the snow reached his waist. In the morning Bodhidharma asked him why he was there. Huike replied that he wanted a teacher to "open the gate of the elixir of universal compassion to liberate all beings".
Bodhidharma refused, saying, “how can you hope for true religion with little virtue, little wisdom, a shallow heart, and an arrogant mind? It would just be a waste of effort.” Finally, to prove his resolve, Huike cut off his arm and presented it to the First Patriarch as a token of his sincerity. Bodhidharma then accepted him as a student, and changed his name from Shenguang to Huike, which means "Wisdom and Capacity"
